{
  "texts": [
    "Depending on their research question, many researchers are interested in fixations, saccades, blinks and perhaps other events.",
    "However, this is not what most eye trackers deliver.",
    "Instead, the eye tracking signal consists of a regularly sampled sequence of eye orientations or gaze positions indicating where the participant looked, often at a high sampling frequency.",
    "As such, a processing step is needed that applies labels to parts of the eye tracker signal, segmenting the signal into episodes that are meaningful and usable for the researcher.",
    "Such methods that process the eye tracking signal into meaningful units such as fixations and saccades are called event classifiers (or event detectors)."
  ]
}